description: From the results of histological studies, the saccus vasculosus was seen more obviously, and lined between the caudal parts of the inferior lobes of the hypothalamus, beneath the glomerular nucleus, referred to as the nucleus glomerulosus. It contained several neurons, as similarly reported in Scyliorhinus canicula [16]andEpinephelus coioides [17]. The succus vasculosus was histologically surrounded by a thin tunica albuginea, as well as a prominent connective tissue. Within its structure wereseveral folded walls, consisting of blood sinuses as well as red blood vessels, covered by pseudostratified cuboidal epithelium on the basement membrane. In this context, these epitheliums could also be classified into 2 epithelial cell types.

In Bregmacerotidae, the brain is cylindrical in general appearance, the
olfactory tract is very short, the surface of the olfactory lobe is almost smooth, the
cerebellar corpus is strikingly depressed, and the inferior lobe, acoustic-lateral area
and vascular sac are not developed.
The pituitary gland and the saccus vasculosus are relatively small relative to most teleosts.

A careful review of the available animal material, including extensive control through sagittal series, revealed a complete absence of the saccus vasculosus sensu strictiori in all vertebrate genera except fish, of which it could not be detected in Cyprinus carpio, Cobitis tania, Belonae acus, Lepadogaster gouanii, or cyprinoids.

The corpora do not begin on the ventral side of the brain, but leave space for the saccus vasculosus.

A small, dense, vascular organ, termed the vascular sac (VS, Fig. 2), lies on the midline adjacent to the ventricle. It is included in the caudal hypothalamus as in Braford and Northcutt ('83). This nucleus, of unknown function, varies in size and structure enormously among teleosts although it is relatively similar in all elasmobranchs (e.g., Harder, '75). In H. burton4 it is a very small structure with folded laminae most visible in parasagittal section. Although the VS is small in H. burtoni relative to other species the nucleus is clearly present, contrary to Laming's ('70) claim that it does not exist in Haplochromis sp.
Inferior lobe or hypothalamic inferior lobe: the inferior lobe did not include the vascular sac and hypophysis.

The saccus vasculosus was a small and capsule-like structure located in the caudal region of the hypothalamus. Histological evaluation showed that it is surrounded by a meninx primitiva, a highly vascularized endomeninx (Fig. 28). Extensive folds were observed in the epithelium (Fig. 28). Coronet cells with a basally located nuclei and supporting glial cells were attached to the epithelium (Fig. 29).
Dorsal to the pituitary gland, a vascularized folded epithelium, the saccus vasculosus, was observed (Figure 1(c)). At 354 D°eff, the cerebellum comprised most of the metencephalon.

Reproductive seasonality in fish is reported to be controlled by hypothalamus/ SV organ which acts as a sensor of seasonal changes in day length [29]. Existence of this organ is already reported in Labeo rohita [59]
It formed from pineal gland around third ventricle, thalamus, hypothalamus, and pituitary gland and saccus vasculosus. T

Immunostaining was also found in saccus vasculosus, thymus, spleen and ovary. The function of the saccus has been suggested to be
mainly concerned with homeostasis of the cerebrospinal
fluid; others have suggested that it may be concerned with
osmoregulation via the activity of ATPase enzymes involved in transport of Na+/K+ and Mg2+/Ca2+ (Jansen
et al. 1981). Observations of the presence of immunoreactive IGF-II (present study) and IGF-I (G Radaelli, M
Patruno, L Maccatrozzo & B Funkenstein, unpublished
observations) in the saccus of S. aurata, together with
previous reports on immunoreactive prolactin receptors in
this organ of S. aurata (Santos et al. 2001) further support
a role in osmoregulation.
In the adult, immunostaining with IGFBP-2 antibody was also found in the saccus vasculosus, ovary and testis.

A decreasing expression trend of LmDyn in the hypothalamus, pituitary, saccus vasculosus, and gonads was observed from stage I to stage V. Photoperiodic experiments in vivo and in vitro showed that the LmDyn expression level in the hypothalamus and saccus vasculosus was higher under long-day photoperiod treatment (16 h light:8 h dark) and lower under short-day photoperiod treatment (8 h light:16 h dark).

The shortened light cycle of 8L:16D significantly upregulates the expression of LmGnRH2 in the hypothalamus, pituitary, saccus vasculosus, and gonads.

description:
The saccus vasculosus was located posterior to the pituitary (Fig. 1C). This organ was easily recognized due to its high vascularization and the presence of coronet cells, characterized by an apical crown of globuletipped cilia protruding into the third ventricle. Supporting cells were also present in this structure, characterized by their apical and triangular nuclei (Fig. 1G, H). The saccus vasculosus microphotograph was taken in a more parasagittal section than the pituitary gland microphotograph and the dashed box indicates the region
of the saccus vasculosus.
